<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-957-456  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 957 456.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Jan 20 1989 v138 n47,756 pB8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computers assuming new roles at law firms. (The Law)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wiehl, Lis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computers find applications in law firms: word processors andinformation services - notably Lexis and Westlaw - transform theprofession; computer programs help neophyte associates and generalpracticioners to draft legal documents; and experiments inartificial intelligence actually mimic the way lawyers think.andO;Some lawyers fear that creativity and innovation might suffer asautomation proceeds.andP;  But law firms already are using expertsystems, which can guide users, generating documents - wills, realestate papers or contracts.andP;  Even more startling: research atuniversities suggest artificial intelligence systems that willsimulate a lawyer's thought processes, actually writing briefs onsubtle questions by distinguishing between similar cases,reasoning by analogy and arguing either side of a question.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Law OfficesArtificial IntelligenceExpert SystemsDocument PreparationWord ProcessingInformation ServicesApplicationsTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>